/* <orly/lang_tests/general/variants_mutual_eval.orly>

   End-to-end test for issue #116 Phase 2c: constructing and consuming
   values of a mutually-recursive variant group.

   `expr` and `stmt` reference each other (and `expr` also itself), forming
   a strongly-connected component of type defs. Each member compiles to its
   own native variant class; cross-member and self-member arms are stored
   boxed as the (statically known) sibling class, so every recursive edge
   resolves to a concrete member type -- no unrolling needed. The whole
   group lives in one combined header.

   Everything composes across the group boundary: alias-constructors
   (`expr.Block(...)`, `stmt.Eval(...)`), exhaustive `when` with payload
   binders that recurse into the *other* member (`eval`/`exec` are mutually
   recursive folds), `is`/`.Tag` destructuring, deep structural `==`, and
   membership in a local set.

   v1 limit (Phase 2c): the values are package-internal. Storing one or
   returning it to a client throws (the sabot type vocabulary cannot yet
   express the recursion), exactly as a single-recursive #103 value did
   before storage landed; and a group arm whose payload is a record or
   container of a sibling is a tracked follow-up.

   Copyright 2010-2026 Atomic Kismet Company

   Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");
   you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.
   You may obtain a copy of the License at

     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0

   Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software
   distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,
   WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.
   See the License for the specific language governing permissions and
   limitations under the License. */

/* A tiny mutually-recursive language: an expression may hold a statement
   (`Block`) or itself (`Neg`); a statement may hold an expression (`Eval`). */
expr is <| Lit(int) | Neg(expr) | Block(stmt) |>;
stmt is <| Done | Eval(expr) |>;

/* Mutually-recursive folds: each descends into the other member. */
eval = ((e) when {
  Lit(n): n;
  Neg(x): 0 - eval(.e: x);
  Block(s): exec(.s: s);
}) where {
  e = given::(expr);
};

exec = ((s) when {
  Done: 0;
  Eval(x): eval(.e: x);
}) where {
  s = given::(stmt);
};

/* Shared fixtures: e1 == e2 structurally, e3 differs. */
e1 = (expr.Block(stmt.Eval(expr.Neg(expr.Lit(5))))) where {};
e2 = (expr.Block(stmt.Eval(expr.Neg(expr.Lit(5))))) where {};
e3 = (expr.Lit(7)) where {};

test {
  /* Folds, including across the member boundary and through self-recursion. */
  t1: eval(.e: expr.Lit(42)) == 42;
  t2: eval(.e: expr.Neg(expr.Lit(5))) == 0 - 5;
  t3: eval(.e: e1) == 0 - 5;
  t4: exec(.s: stmt.Done()) == 0;
  t5: exec(.s: stmt.Eval(expr.Lit(8))) == 8;

  /* Deep structural equality reaches through the boxed members. */
  t6: e1 == e2;
  t7: e1 != e3;

  /* is / .Tag destructuring, chaining across members. */
  t8: e1 is Block;
  t9: not (e1 is Lit);
  t10: (e1.Block) is Eval;
  t11: ((e1.Block).Eval) is Neg;
  t12: (((e1.Block).Eval).Neg).Lit == 5;

  /* Recursive group values in a local set: the duplicate collapses. */
  t13: length_of {e1, e2, e3} == 2;
};
